@everyone from my journal five years ago yesterday:

"I’ve been working with Hendrick and Iggy getting the discord server up, and just sent out a bunch of invites. It’s cool to see the beginnings of a community happen. I’m getting all these creative ideas just thinking about what’s possible. It’s also a testament to just DOING things. Even if there isn’t a solid goal in mind. When you do things, you learn things."

Big love to @hendrick and @1ggy who were the first ones involved to help make this place happen. I'm so proud of all of you for helping keep this community thriving. You all put kindness and curiosity and patience first, and THAT is what makes this place special. An island in the sea of fuckery that is the internet. I appreciate you all, my friends!

@everyone a reminder that two very strict rules we have here are "no self-promotion" and "no politics." It keeps this place focused on helping each other make better records. The mods make exceptions for things that are part of an existing, productive conversation. 

If you want to discuss politics, promote your music, or explain to strangers how technology oppresses people, please go do that at a place called EVERYWHERE ELSE ON THE INTERNET.

Love to you all. ❤️

@Edward Rivera @BatMeckley (and everyone else) really appreciate this discussion. Always so insightful. I am probably guilty of not giving enough context in my original post, which probably sparked some confusion (however everything you guys said was probably useful for the onlookers) 
I will say that this situation has been going on for a while now, and a lot has been done to try and resolve things - but if you knew the specifics of the situation, you may realize why its such a sticky one. (I cant really say it publicly on the internet here, I know some people on the discord are mutual friends, but i can talk more about it in dms if someome wants)

Either way, I'm currently in a situation where I'm lucky enough to be very busy, and working on other records that I'm VERY excited about,  for similar money. I only have so much time and energy and its hard to give my 100% to everything. It deeply bothers me when I cant do everything that I personally can to make a record as good as I think it can be - but at this stage I've to make a  decision, do I spend more time on saving a sinking ship? Or do I let it be, after months of doing what I can, so that I can focus on projects that I'm truly excited about with great people? Im leaning towards the latter I think

@oaklandmatt Thank you for the suggestions.

I'm very close to this point now. I'm doing 4 octave scale runs with both hands at various tempos to focus on consistency of fingering and of tone. The next frontier is doing a variation of these runs where one hand starts on a scale different interval (going up in 3rds, 4ths, etc...)

The exercise that's challenging me at the moment has been doing wide arpeggios (sometimes with intervals of a 7th or more) up and down a two octaves. I'm taking it slow and becoming more consistent, but I know I'm likely to start hitting a wall as I get them up to a quicker tempo, hence the renewed focus on really getting my technique right at these tempos.

I've very much internalized the concept of "Slow is smooth. Smooth is fast." I'm starting things slow and not moving on until I can do them flawlessly at glacial tempos.

@ehutton21 I think you're right about a teacher. LA is undoubtedly full of good ones. A lesson a week should help me to orient myself in the right direction.

Thank you for all of the insight.
